## CHAPTER I - GENERAL PROVISIONS

### Article 1 - Subject matter
This Regulation lays down requirements for the design and manufacture of personal protective equipment (PPE) which is to be made available on the market, in order to ensure the health and safety of users and establish rules on the free movement of PPE in the Union.

### Article 2 - Scope
This Regulation applies to PPE which is intended to be made available on the Union market.

For the purposes of this Regulation, PPE means:
(a) equipment designed and manufactured to be worn or held by a person for protection against one or more risks to that person's health or safety;
(b) interchangeable components for equipment referred to in point (a) which are essential for its protective function;
(c) connexion systems for equipment referred to in point (a) which are not held or worn by a person, but which are designed to connect that equipment to an external device or to a reliable anchorage point, and which are not designed to be permanently fixed and do not require fastening works before use.

### Article 3 - Definitions
For the purposes of this Regulation, the following definitions apply:
(1) 'making available on the market' means any supply of PPE for distribution, consumption or use on the Union market in the course of a commercial activity, whether in return for payment or free of charge;
(2) 'manufacturer' means any natural or legal person who manufactures PPE or who has PPE designed or manufactured, and markets that PPE under his name or trademark;
(3) 'authorised representative' means any natural or legal person established within the Union who has received a written mandate from a manufacturer to act on his behalf in relation to specified tasks;
(4) 'importer' means any natural or legal person established within the Union who places PPE from a third country on the Union market;
(5) 'distributor' means any natural or legal person in the supply chain, other than the manufacturer or the importer, who makes PPE available on the market.

## CHAPTER II - OBLIGATIONS OF ECONOMIC OPERATORS

### Article 8 - Obligations of manufacturers
1. Manufacturers shall ensure that the PPE which they place on the market has been designed and manufactured in accordance with the essential health and safety requirements set out in Annex II.

2. Manufacturers shall draw up the technical documentation referred to in Annex III and carry out the relevant conformity assessment procedure referred to in Article 19 or have it carried out.

3. Where compliance of PPE with the applicable requirements has been demonstrated by the conformity assessment procedure, manufacturers shall draw up an EU declaration of conformity and affix the CE marking.

4. Manufacturers shall keep the technical documentation and the EU declaration of conformity for 10 years after the PPE has been placed on the market.

### Article 9 - Authorised representatives
1. A manufacturer may, by a written mandate, appoint an authorised representative.

2. The obligations laid down in Article 8(1) and the obligation to draw up technical documentation shall not form part of the authorised representative's mandate.

### Article 10 - Obligations of importers
1. Importers shall place only compliant PPE on the market.

2. Before placing PPE on the market, importers shall ensure that the appropriate conformity assessment procedure has been carried out by the manufacturer.

## CHAPTER III - CONFORMITY OF PPE

### Article 19 - Conformity assessment procedures
1. Before placing PPE on the market, manufacturers shall undertake a conformity assessment procedure in accordance with Articles 20 to 24.

2. The conformity assessment procedures are:
(a) Module A: Internal production control (for Category I PPE);
(b) Module B: EU type-examination (for Category II and III PPE);
(c) Module C2: Supervised product checks at random intervals (for Category II PPE);
(d) Module D: Quality assurance of the production process (for Category III PPE).

### Article 20 - Category I PPE
Category I PPE includes exclusively the following minimal risks:
(a) superficial mechanical injury;
(b) contact with cleaning materials of weak action;
(c) contact with hot surfaces which do not exceed 50°C;
(d) damage to the eyes due to exposure to sunlight (other than during observation of the sun);
(e) atmospheric conditions that are not of an extreme nature.

### Article 21 - Category II PPE
Category II includes risks other than those listed in Categories I and III.

### Article 22 - Category III PPE
Category III PPE includes exclusively the risks that may cause very serious consequences such as death or irreversible damage to health relating to the following:
(a) substances and mixtures which are hazardous to health;
(b) atmospheres with oxygen deficiency;
(c) harmful biological agents;
(d) ionising radiation;
(e) high-temperature environments;
(f) low-temperature environments;
(g) falling from a height;
(h) electric shock and live working;
(i) drowning;
(j) cuts by hand-held chainsaws;
(k) high-pressure jets;
(l) bullet wounds or knife stabs;
(m) harmful noise.

## ANNEX II - ESSENTIAL HEALTH AND SAFETY REQUIREMENTS

### 1. General requirements applicable to all PPE
PPE must be designed and manufactured so that, in the foreseeable conditions of use for which it is intended, it protects the user against the relevant risks.

The manufacturer must ensure that:
(a) the PPE is free of defects and satisfies the provisions applicable to it;
(b) the protective characteristics of the PPE are not adversely affected by the user's normal behaviour;
(c) the PPE can be easily worn and correctly adjusted;
(d) the PPE does not restrict the user's necessary movements or sensory perception.

### 2. Additional requirements common to several classes or types of PPE
#### 2.1 PPE incorporating adjustment systems
PPE incorporating adjustment systems must be designed and manufactured so that these systems cannot be accidentally disengaged during use.

#### 2.2 PPE enclosing the parts of the body to be protected
PPE enclosing the parts of the body to be protected must be designed and manufactured so that it allows the necessary perspiration.

#### 2.3 PPE for eyes, face, and respiratory protection
PPE for the eyes, face, and respiratory protection must be designed and manufactured so that:
(a) the field of vision is not unduly reduced;
(b) the optical characteristics of eye protectors do not impair the user's vision;
(c) respiratory protective devices provide adequate breathable air.

### 3. Information supplied by the manufacturer
The manufacturer must ensure that each item of PPE is accompanied by instructions and information in the official language(s) of the Member State in which it is to be made available on the market.

The instructions must include:
(a) the storage, use, cleaning, maintenance, servicing and disinfection conditions;
(b) the performance levels achieved during testing;
(c) the appropriate accessories and spare components;
(d) the obsolescence deadline or period of obsolescence;
(e) the meaning of any markings;
(f) the risks against which the PPE is designed to protect.

## ANNEX III - TECHNICAL DOCUMENTATION

The technical documentation must contain all relevant data or details of the means used by the manufacturer to ensure that PPE complies with the requirements relating to it. It must cover the design, manufacture and operation of the PPE.

The technical documentation shall contain:
(a) a general description of the PPE;
(b) design drawings and schemes of components, sub-assemblies, circuits, etc.;
(c) descriptions and explanations necessary for the understanding of those drawings and schemes and the operation of the PPE;
(d) a list of the harmonised standards and/or other technical specifications applied;
(e) the results of design calculations, examinations, and tests;
(f) test reports;
(g) a description of the means used by the manufacturer during the production of the PPE to ensure the conformity of the PPE produced with the design specifications.

## 1. Introduction

This guidance document provides recommendations for the submission of premarket notification (510(k)) applications to the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for surgical masks and surgical N95 respirators.

### 1.1 Scope
This guidance applies to:
(a) Surgical masks intended to provide barrier protection against fluids and particulate materials;
(b) Surgical N95 respirators intended to provide both fluid resistance and particulate filtration efficiency;
(c) Filtering facepiece respirators intended for use in healthcare settings.

### 1.2 Device Classification
Surgical masks are classified under 21 CFR 878.4040 as Class II medical devices.

## 2. Predicate Device Comparison

### 2.1 Selection of Predicate Device
The 510(k) submission shall identify a legally marketed predicate device to which substantial equivalence is claimed.

### 2.2 Comparison Table
The submission shall include a comparison table identifying similarities and differences between the subject device and the predicate device in the following areas:
(a) Intended use;
(b) Technological characteristics;
(c) Performance specifications;
(d) Materials of construction;
(e) Design features.

## 3. Performance Testing

### 3.1 Fluid Resistance Testing
Surgical masks and surgical N95 respirators shall be tested for fluid resistance in accordance with ASTM F1862.

The following performance levels are recognized:
(a) Level 1: 80 mmHg fluid resistance
(b) Level 2: 120 mmHg fluid resistance
(c) Level 3: 160 mmHg fluid resistance

### 3.2 Bacterial Filtration Efficiency (BFE)
The bacterial filtration efficiency shall be determined in accordance with ASTM F2101.

Minimum acceptable BFE: 95% for surgical masks.

### 3.3 Particulate Filtration Efficiency (PFE)
The particulate filtration efficiency shall be determined in accordance with ASTM F2299.

Minimum acceptable PFE: 95% at 0.1 micron particle size for surgical masks.

### 3.4 Differential Pressure (Breathability)
The differential pressure shall be measured in accordance with MIL-M-36954C.

Maximum acceptable differential pressure: 5.0 mm H2O/cm² for surgical masks.

### 3.5 Flammability Testing
Surgical masks shall be tested for flammability in accordance with 16 CFR Part 1610.

Minimum acceptable classification: Class 1 (normal flammability).

## 4. Biocompatibility

### 4.1 Evaluation Requirements
The biocompatibility of the device materials shall be evaluated in accordance with ISO 10993.

### 4.2 Required Tests
The following biocompatibility tests are typically required:
(a) Cytotoxicity (ISO 10993-5);
(b) Sensitization (ISO 10993-10);
(c) Irritation (ISO 10993-10).

## 5. Labeling

### 5.1 Device Label
Each device shall bear a label containing:
(a) The manufacturer's name and address;
(b) The device name and model number;
(c) The statement 'Single Use' or 'Reusable' as applicable;
(d) The fluid resistance level (for surgical masks);
(e) Instructions for use.

### 5.2 Instructions for Use
The instructions for use shall include:
(a) Intended use and indications;
(b) Contraindications;
(c) Warnings and precautions;
(d) Instructions for donning and doffing;
(e) Storage conditions;
(f) Shelf life.

## 6. Quality System Regulation

### 6.1 Compliance Requirements
Manufacturers shall comply with the Quality System Regulation (21 CFR Part 820).

### 6.2 Required Procedures
The quality system shall include procedures for:
(a) Design controls;
(b) Document controls;
(c) Purchasing controls;
(d) Identification and traceability;
(e) Production and process controls;
(f) Acceptance activities;
(g) Nonconforming product;
(h) Corrective and preventive action;
(i) Labeling and packaging controls;
(j) Handling, storage, distribution, and installation;
(k) Records;
(l) Servicing;
(m) Statistical techniques.

## 7. Clinical Data

### 7.1 When Required
Clinical data may be required when:
(a) The device raises new questions of safety or effectiveness;
(b) The device has different intended use from the predicate;
(c) The technological characteristics differ significantly from the predicate.

### 7.2 Types of Clinical Data
Clinical data may include:
(a) Clinical studies;
(b) Published literature;
(c) Post-market surveillance data.

## 8. Submission Format

### 8.1 Required Elements
The 510(k) submission shall include:
(a) Device description;
(b) Indications for use;
(c) Predicate device comparison;
(d) Performance testing data;
(e) Biocompatibility data;
(f) Sterilization validation (if applicable);
(g) Shelf life validation;
(h) Software documentation (if applicable);
(i) Electromagnetic compatibility (if applicable);
(j) Labeling;
(k) Quality system information.

### 8.2 eCopy Requirements
The submission shall be provided in electronic format (eCopy) in accordance with FDA guidance.
